"English (Norfolk): habitational name, chiefly from Paston in Norfolk, probably derived from an Old English personal name <i>Pæcci</i> (genitive <i>Pæcces</i>) or Old English <i>pæsc(e)</i> (the source of northern English dialect <i>pash</i> ‘puddle’) + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’.","English (West Midlands): sometimes a variant of <b>Patstone</b>, a habitational name chiefly from the lost <i>Padston(e)</i> in Bromsgrove (Worcestershire), and occasionally from Padson in Inwardleigh (Devon). The Worcestershire placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Padda</i> (genitive <i>Paddes</i>) + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The etymology of the Devon placename is uncertain due to a lack of medieval forms, though an early spelling suggests the final element is Old English <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Clement","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Late Latin name <i>Clemens</i> (genitive <i>Clementis</i>) meaning ‘merciful’. This was borne by several early saints, notably the fourth pope and the early Christian theologian Clement of Alexandria (Titus Flavius Clemens,   ad  ?150–?215 )."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":0,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":25,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":38,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of 